Some Random Exploratory Data Analysis on The NYC Flights Dataset

Question 1

Using the flights data frame discussed in the class, visualize the distribution of departure times (a). Across the year

flights_n <- flights %>%
  filter(!is.na(dep_time)) %>%
  select(year,month,day,hour,minute,carrier,dep_delay,arr_delay,distance) %>%
  mutate(
    dep_time = make_datetime(year,month,day,hour,minute)
    
  )
flights_n %>%
  ggplot(aes(dep_time)) +
  #geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = month,y = dep_time))
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 86400)

flights %>%
  ggplot(aes(hour)) + 
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 1)

Above Are Two Plots Showing Frequency Polygons (i) There are higher number of flights during August,September. There also sudden decrease in the freq of number of flights during mid of febuary and march. There (ii) Seconds Plot is the frequency polygon of No. of flights according to their their Hourly departure time across the whole year .telling us the total count of flights on different hours throughout a day. we can see that the number start increasing from 5 and goes maximum no. flights at around the morning hour of 7-8 ,decreasing after that to a local minimum around the afternoon hours and then again rising to a maximum in the evening hours.

(b). During the Month December 2013

flights_n %>%
  filter(year == 2013,month == 12) %>%
  ggplot(aes(dep_time)) + 
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 7200)

flights %>%
  filter(year == 2013,month == 12) %>%
  ggplot(aes(hour)) + 
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 1)

Above Are Two Plots Showing Frequency Polygons (i) First Plot is the fequency polygon of No. of flights according to their departure time across the month of december. (ii) Seconds Plot is the frequency polygon of No. of flights according to their their Hourly departure time .telling us the total count of flights on different hours throughout a day in the month of december. we can see that this pattern is nearly identical to the yearly plot given above.

Question 2

Using the R packages discussed in the class, explore the relationship between the distance and average delay for each carrier and a particular time period of the day (e.g. group observations according to hours of the day).

#ggplot(data = flights_n)

flights_g <- group_by(flights_n,carrier,hour)
flight_m <- summarise(flights_g,avg_delay = mean(dep_delay,na.rm = TRUE) + mean(arr_delay,na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(data = flight_m) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = hour,y = avg_delay,color = carrier),alpha = 2/3) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = hour,y = avg_delay))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

flights_t <- group_by(flights_n,carrier,hour)
flight_j <- summarise(flights_t,avg_delay = mean(dep_delay,na.rm = TRUE) + mean(arr_delay,na.rm = TRUE),avg_dist = mean(distance,na.rm = TRUE))
  
ggplot(data = flight_j) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = avg_dist,y = avg_delay,color = carrier,size = hour)) +
